    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Richlands Station on the Springfield Central line gives the suburb a commuter infrastructure advantage that its price point does not yet fully reflect. The station includes a substantial park-and-ride facility, meaning buyers who drive from surrounding areas such as Doolandella and Durack also gravitate toward Richlands for its transport hub. Direct rail to the CBD, combined with immediate Ipswich Motorway access on the eastern boundary, makes the suburb unusually well-connected for its distance from the city.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The housing stock is a genuine mix: older post-war homes on generous blocks in the suburb's established sections sit alongside newer residential estates developed from the 2000s onward. The newer estates offer the turn-key presentation that families and first home buyers prefer, while the older homes on larger allotments attract investors and buyers who see value in land. The IKEA and major retail precinct on the eastern edge near the Ipswich Motorway adds a convenience layer that buyers from neighbouring Inala and Forest Lake also use regularly, reinforcing Richlands as a local commercial hub.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
      <div style="flex:1; min-width:200px; background:#fff; padding:1.75rem; border-left:3px solid #b98229; border-radius:16px;">
